Compressed Federated Reinforcement Learning with a Generative Model

Author information scrubbed for double-blind reviewing â€ƒâ€ƒ Ali Beikmohammadi (âœ‰) 11 0000-0003-4884-4600 â€ƒâ€ƒ Sarit Khirirat 22 0000-0003-4473-2011 â€ƒâ€ƒ Sindri MagnÃºsson 11 0000-0002-6617-8683
Abstract

Reinforcement learning has recently gained unprecedented popularity, yet it still grapples with sample inefficiency. Addressing this challenge, federated reinforcement learning (FedRL) has emerged, wherein agents collaboratively learn a single policy by aggregating local estimations. However, this aggregation step incurs significant communication costs. In this paper, we propose CompFedRL, a communication-efficient FedRL approach incorporating both periodic aggregation and (direct/error-feedback) compression mechanisms. Specifically, we consider compressed federated Qğ‘„Q-learning with a generative model setup, where a central server learns an optimal Qğ‘„Q-function by periodically aggregating compressed Qğ‘„Q-estimates from local agents. For the first time, we characterize the impact of these two mechanisms (which have remained elusive) by providing a finite-time analysis of our algorithm, demonstrating strong convergence behaviors when utilizing either direct or error-feedback compression. Our bounds indicate improved solution accuracy concerning the number of agents and other federated hyperparameters while simultaneously reducing communication costs. To corroborate our theory, we also conduct in-depth numerical experiments to verify our findings, considering Top-Kğ¾K and Sparsified-Kğ¾K sparsification operators.

1 Introduction

Reinforcement learning (RL) [53] has advanced many progresses in solving several decision-making applications, such as game playing [46], optimal control [7], autonomous driving [68], and recommendation systemsÂ [62]. In traditional RL algorithms, an agent learns and makes the best sequential actions within a Markov Decision Process (MDP) that maximize long-term rewards, even without the full knowledge of its model parameters. This learning process involves the agent repeatedly interacting with the environment, generating data that can then be used to refine its decision-making strategy.

However, training RL models under high-dimensional environments is challenging, because the RL models require (1) high volumes of storage being directly proportional to the size of state and action spaces, and (2) high sample complexity to find an optimal policy, i.e. a large number of interactions between the agent and the environment [8, 6]. Training RL models with limited data often leads to poor performance in high output variability, while sequentially generating vast volumes of data is computationally expensive. Consequently, many practical RL implementations resort to parallel data sampling from the environment by multiple agents [45].

Recently, many RL algorithms have been modified to leverage federated learning (FL), known as federated RL (FedRL), to obtain faster training performance and improved accuracy. FL is a popular multi-agent framework that ensures privacy and securityÂ [42] since it does not require the agents to transmit their private data over the network, which is computationally prohibitive, especially when the data is sizeable, and the network is resource-constrained. At each communication round of FedRL algorithms, the central server updates the model parameters, based on aggregations of local model updates transmitted by all the agents. Previous studies on FedRL algorithms primarily focus on addressing challenges such as robustness to adversarial attacks [67, 26], environment heterogeneity [31, 60, 69], behavior policy heterogeneity [65], and sample complexities [23, 34]. Unfortunately, none of these studies addresses the communication performance bottleneck of FedRL algorithms that interact with high-dimensional environments.

A commonly used approach to reduce communication costs is to apply compression, e.g., sparsification and quantization, alongside periodic aggregation. Compressing the information reduces its size before it is transmitted and is beneficial for running optimization algorithms over bandwidth-limited networks. The impact of compression on optimization algorithms under both centralized and federated settings has been extensively studied, e.g. in [1, 2, 61, 51, 33, 11]. Unfortunately, very limited works have studied compressed FedRL algorithms. Multi-agent RL with compressed updates has been studied in [44]. However, the result inÂ [44] is limited to TD learning with linear function approximation, and they neither utilized periodic averaging nor analyzed direct compression.

2 Related Work

Single-agent RL Algorithms.

Existing works have extensively investigated the convergence guarantees of many RL algorithms, such as TD-learning and Qğ‘„Q-learning algorithms, primarily on the single-agent environment under various conditions. TD-learning algorithms are shown to have asymptotic convergence in the on-policy setting by [56, 55, 13] and in the off-policy setting by [39, 70], while the algorithms attain non-asymptotic convergence (or finite-sample bounds) in the on-policy setting by [21, 35, 12, 50, 29, 16] and in the off-policy setting by [15, 16]. Furthermore, initially proposed by [63], the Qğ‘„Q-learning algorithm has been extensively studied its convergence properties in varied settings. For instance, on the one hand, the asymptotic convergence of the Qğ‘„Q-learning algorithm was established by [57, 30, 10, 54, 14, 13]. On the other hand, the finite-time convergence of Qğ‘„Q-learning algorithm under synchronous sampling, also known as RL with a generative model, was proved by [25, 5, 59, 15, 36, 27], and under asynchronous sampling (known as Markovian sampling) was studied by [25, 5, 48, 36, 37, 16]. Our work operates within RL with a generative model, but focuses on a multi-agent collaborative federated setup, emphasizing communication-efficient methodologies, which requires an analysis framework different from traditional single-agent RL analyses.

Distributed and Federated RL Algorithms.

Several recent studies have introduced distributed variants of RL algorithms aimed at expediting training processes [45, 24, 3]. Theoretical examinations of the convergence properties of these distributed RL algorithms have also been explored in recent literature across various scenarios, including decentralized stochastic approximation [22, 52, 58, 71, 44], TD learning with linear function approximation [60], and off-policy TD in actor-critic algorithms [18]. Additionally, [17, 49] have conducted analyses on the finite-time convergence of distributed actor-critic algorithms. Nevertheless, all of these investigations focus on decentralized setups, where agents communicate with their neighbors following each local update. On the other hand, there are some studies that consider a federated setting, with each agent performing multiple local updates between successive communication rounds, thereby resulting in communication savings. This includes TD learning with linear function approximation [20, 19, 34], off-policy TD learning [34], SARSA with linear function approximation [69], and Qğ‘„Q-learning [34, 65, 31]. Our work, akin to the setup of [65], centers on a federated Qğ‘„Q-learning algorithm but sets itself apart by integrating various compression strategies to enhance communication efficiency.

Communication-Efficient Learning Algorithms.

Many compression schemes, i.e. sparsification and/or quantization, have been used for optimization algorithms to train state-of-the-art learning models (e.g. AlexNet, VGG19, and ResNet152) under resource-constrained networks [1, 64, 61, 41]. These compression schemes can be either unbiased (such as QSGD [1], TernGrad [64], and ATOMO [61]) or biased (e.g. Top-Kğ¾K[2], normalized gradient [40] and sign compression [9]). Despite communication benefits, optimization algorithms with compression often have poor convergence performance. For instance, the biased compression algorithms are shown to fail to converge for simple problems [11, 33]. To address the problem of direct compression, several studies [51, 33, 2, 32, 38, 28, 43] have proposed error-feedback mechanisms which leverage memory of previous compression errors to mitigate compression biases for distributed and federated learning algorithms under various settings. None of the mentioned works has investigated communication-efficient learning in the context of RL. The only existing study, [44], examines error-feedback compression, focusing on TD learning with linear function approximation in distributed learning, contrasting with our synchronous federated Qğ‘„Q-learning approach, where aggregation occurs periodically. We investigate both direct and error-feedback compression operators, offering a thorough FedRL convergence analysis.

6 Experiments

In this section, we carry out numerical experiments to showcase the effectiveness of the CompFedRLÂ algorithm.

Setup.

We examine five variations of the noisy grid-world environment, some of which contain walls (as illustrated in Figure 5). Details regarding these environments and more results can be found in Appendix 0.C.1 and Appendix 0.C.2, respectively. The Qğ‘„Q-function is initialized with zero entries, and we set Î³=0.8ğ›¾0.8\gamma=0.8. After each round of communication tğ‘¡t, we evaluate the estimated Qğ‘„Q through the root mean square error (RMSE) between the estimated QÂ¯tsubscriptÂ¯ğ‘„ğ‘¡\overline{Q}_{t} and the optimal Qâˆ—superscriptğ‘„Q^{*}.

To measure the communication efficiency of compression, we not only monitor the RMSE in communication rounds but also track the number of bits used by each agent. We evaluate communicated bits by considering floating point precision (FPP) to be 32 bits. Then, in each round of communication, for FedRL (i.e., CompFedRLÂ without compression), CompFedRLÂ with Top-Kğ¾K, and CompFedRLÂ with Sparsified-Kğ¾K, the payload consumes |S|â€‹|A|Ã—Fâ€‹Pâ€‹Pğ‘†ğ´ğ¹ğ‘ƒğ‘ƒ|S||A|\times FPP bits, KÃ—(âŒˆlog2â¡(|S|â€‹|A|)âŒ‰+Fâ€‹Pâ€‹P)ğ¾subscript2ğ‘†ğ´ğ¹ğ‘ƒğ‘ƒK\times\left(\lceil\log_{2}(|S||A|)\rceil+FPP\right) bits, and Kâ€²Ã—(âŒˆlog2â¡(|S|â€‹|A|)âŒ‰+Fâ€‹Pâ€‹P)superscriptğ¾â€²subscript2ğ‘†ğ´ğ¹ğ‘ƒğ‘ƒK^{\prime}\times\left(\lceil\log_{2}(|S||A|)\rceil+FPP\right) bits, respectively. Here, Kâ€²superscriptğ¾â€²K^{\prime} is the size of the selected set by Sparsified-Kğ¾KÂ to be sent, and the factor âŒˆlog2â¡(|S|â€‹|A|)âŒ‰subscript2ğ‘†ğ´\lceil\log_{2}(|S||A|)\rceil comes from indicating Kğ¾K (Kâ€²superscriptğ¾â€²K^{\prime}) indices in the dimension of the state-action space.

Communication Efficiency of CompFedRL.

Figure 1 demonstrates the impact of both Sparsified-Kğ¾KÂ and Top-Kğ¾KÂ on reducing communication payload with the server and on convergence. Transitioning from local epochs of K=1ğ¾1K=1 to K=10ğ¾10K=10 showcases consistent convergence behavior despite a tenfold reduction in communication frequency, underscoring the practicality of both periodic aggregation and compression mechanisms. A comparative analysis between Sparsified-Kğ¾KÂ and Top-Kğ¾KÂ reveals that Top-Kğ¾KÂ demonstrates lower residual error and converges to a point comparable to FedRL, as discussed in Section 5.2, where it was highlighted that BiasedCompÂ does not incur a residual error term due to compression. Conversely, with Sparsified-Kğ¾K, an increase in compression leads to a corresponding increase in residual error.

Convergence speedup.

Local updating and the number of agents improve the performance of CompFedRL, as shown in Figure 2. The left plot shows substantial communication reduction by local updating (e.g. 101010 times bits saving for K=10ğ¾10K=10 against K=1ğ¾1K=1) and confirms TheoremÂ 5.1 andÂ 5.2 that, given a fixed step size, an increase in the number of agents lowers residual error, improving convergence performance in RMSE. From the right plot, an interesting observation is that a higher number of agents allows for larger learning rates, which accelerates the convergence speed to attain almost the same target Ïµitalic-Ïµ\epsilon-accuracy.

Impact of Federated Parameter Î²ğ›½\beta and Learning Rate Î·ğœ‚\eta.

Figure 3 and 4 demonstrate the trade-off between the convergence speed and solution accuracy when adjusting Î·ğœ‚\eta and Î²ğ›½\beta. Increasing Î·ğœ‚\eta improves the speed while worsening the accuracy, as confirmed by TheoremÂ 5.1 andÂ 5.2 (see FigureÂ 4). Not captured by our theory, adjusting Î²ğ›½\beta shows the same trade-off as Î·ğœ‚\eta as shown by Figure 3. Changes in Î·ğœ‚\eta affect residual error higher than adjustments in Î²ğ›½\beta, as supported by our non-asymptotic results emphasizing the dependency of most error terms on Î·ğœ‚\eta. Finally, thanks to its error-feedback mechanism, Top-Kğ¾KÂ shows greater robustness than Sparsified-Kğ¾KÂ to these parameter tunings.

7 Conclusion

We have proposed CompFedRL, a communication-efficient federated Qğ‘„Q-learning algorithm that utilizes local epochs and compression to attain strong convergence performance while saving communication costs. Under synchronous settings, we derive the non-asymptotic convergence of the algorithm using both unbiased and biased compression. Our theory suggests speed up with respect to the number of agents, and under certain choices of hyper-parameters CompFedRLÂ attains the sample complexity that nearly matches the lower bound by [36]. Experiments on the noisy grid-world environment corroborate our analyses and illustrate the benefits of periodically compressed updating and the number of agents on convergence performance of CompFedRLÂ in terms of communication efficiency and solution accuracy. Our empirical results also affirm the speed-and-accuracy trade-off when adjusting the learning rates and federated parameters.

Appendix 0.C Details of Experiments

0.C.1 Environments

We use five noisy variants of the grid-world environment, a basic grid-based simulation often used in RL experiments, as shown in Figure 5. In this environment, agents navigate a grid composed of various cells, including walls, empty spaces, and a goal state. Actions available to the agent include moving up, down, left, or right. The state of the environment is represented by the current position of the agent within the grid. Rewards are defined based on the agentâ€™s interactions with the environment; reaching the goal state yields a positive reward +11+1, while taking a non-valid action, such as trying to move through a wall or exit the grid, incurs a penalty âˆ’11-1 and the agent stays in the same position. To introduce noise into the environment, a clipped Gaussian noise model is employed, with the specified standard deviation and clipping threshold, set at 0.5 (i.e., clipâ€‹{ğ’©â€‹(Î¼=0,Ïƒ2=0.5),âˆ’0.5,0.5}clipğ’©formulae-sequenceğœ‡0superscriptğœ20.50.50.5\textsf{clip}\{\mathcal{N}(\mu=0,\sigma^{2}=0.5),-0.5,0.5\}). This noise affects the agentâ€™s interaction, simulating real-world uncertainties and imperfections in the environment.
